1
00:00:01,501 --> 00:00:03,833
"For every action,
there is an opposite
and equal reaction."

2
00:00:03,937 --> 00:00:06,735
Who?
Isaac Newton,
third law of motion.

3
00:00:06,806 --> 00:00:11,266
And how does that apply
to the nature of man?
Anyone? Shawn.

4
00:00:11,344 --> 00:00:13,039
You push, they push back.

5
00:00:13,113 --> 00:00:14,205
Correct. Why?

6
00:00:14,280 --> 00:00:16,305
Because man is
a stupid creature

7
00:00:16,383 --> 00:00:18,351
who'd rather fight
than use his brain.

8
00:00:18,752 --> 00:00:20,743
And what idiot said that?

9
00:00:21,921 --> 00:00:23,047
BOTH: You did.

10
00:00:24,624 --> 00:00:27,559
The name of the game
is survival, sports fans.

11
00:00:27,627 --> 00:00:29,322
In order to survive,
you've got to fight.

12
00:00:29,396 --> 00:00:31,261
And if you fight,
you better damn well win.

13
00:00:31,331 --> 00:00:36,030
Because if you don't win,
and you don't use your brain,
then what happens? Gus?

14
00:00:36,102 --> 00:00:37,126
You lose?

15
00:00:37,203 --> 00:00:40,695
And for this troop,
that is not an option.
<i>Comprende?</i>

16
00:00:40,774 --> 00:00:41,763
BOTH: Sir, yes, sir!

17
00:00:41,841 --> 00:00:47,143
Because losing
is for lowlifes.
Losing is for quitters.

18
00:00:47,313 --> 00:00:50,146
Are you boys lowlifes?
Are you boys quitters?

19
00:00:50,216 --> 00:00:51,513
BOTH: Sir, no, sir!

20
00:00:51,584 --> 00:00:53,677
Troop 101, ten-hut!

21
00:00:55,255 --> 00:00:57,849
Gentlemen,
we are about to embark on

22
00:00:57,924 --> 00:01:01,223
the Junior Bobcat Manual's
infamous Exercise Number 32,

23
00:01:01,294 --> 00:01:03,819
the launching
of a solid fuel rocket.

24
00:01:04,297 --> 00:01:07,391
Now, one of you lucky grunts
is gonna nab this thing

25
00:01:07,467 --> 00:01:09,560
and you're gonna
haul ass back to me.

26
00:01:10,003 --> 00:01:12,301
The prize?
A hot fudge sundae.

27
00:01:12,772 --> 00:01:16,264
But if you lose?
What does the loser get,
Shawn?

28
00:01:16,342 --> 00:01:17,809
He gets to
look on with envy.

29
00:01:17,877 --> 00:01:20,903
That is correct.
He gets to look on with envy.

30
00:01:21,448 --> 00:01:24,417
Because that, gentlemen,
is the American way.

31
00:01:26,586 --> 00:01:28,076
On your marks.

32
00:01:29,522 --> 00:01:30,511
(TICKING)

33
00:01:31,224 --> 00:01:32,418
Ready.

34
00:01:33,760 --> 00:01:34,852
Set.

35
00:01:39,232 --> 00:01:40,256
Go!

36
00:02:01,654 --> 00:02:02,678
What's this?

37
00:02:02,755 --> 00:02:03,915
A parachute.

38
00:02:04,491 --> 00:02:06,516
I sent you after a rocket.

39
00:02:06,826 --> 00:02:09,659
Shawn?
Where's my rocket?

40
00:02:10,463 --> 00:02:12,226
I thought he had it.

41
00:02:24,777 --> 00:02:27,109
A shortcut!
You took a shortcut!

42
00:02:28,615 --> 00:02:29,980
A shortcut, huh?

43
00:02:32,018 --> 00:02:33,315
Prove it.

44
00:02:34,988 --> 00:02:37,616
I'll tell you what,
I beat you this time,

45
00:02:39,092 --> 00:02:40,855
I'm eating the sundae.

46
00:02:50,103 --> 00:02:51,365
Ooh, just in time.

47
00:02:51,437 --> 00:02:52,461
For what?

48
00:02:52,672 --> 00:02:55,607
The annual Civil War
re-enactors meltdown.

49
00:02:55,675 --> 00:02:57,040
The event isn't
until next weekend.

50
00:02:57,177 --> 00:02:58,701
Yeah,
but this is the best part,
the rehearsal.

51
00:02:58,778 --> 00:03:00,177
This is what
they should charge for.

52
00:03:00,246 --> 00:03:01,941
Form battle lines!

53
00:03:03,383 --> 00:03:04,975
Prepare muskets!

54
00:03:05,051 --> 00:03:06,848
Is that Lassiter?
Yes, it is.

55
00:03:06,920 --> 00:03:08,251
What died on his face?

56
00:03:09,556 --> 00:03:11,786
Charge!

57
00:03:12,392 --> 00:03:13,984
(MEN YELLING)

58
00:03:23,536 --> 00:03:24,525
(GRUNTING)

59
00:03:34,013 --> 00:03:36,311
Stop, stop, stop!
Stop!

60
00:03:36,683 --> 00:03:37,672
(HORN BLOWING)

61
00:03:39,285 --> 00:03:42,413
Okay, guys,
that was better.

62
00:03:42,488 --> 00:03:44,820
(STAMMERING) Really.
It was good, actually.

63
00:03:46,559 --> 00:03:48,186
Okay, it wasn't good.

64
00:03:48,261 --> 00:03:49,990
Look, guys,

65
00:03:50,930 --> 00:03:54,457
I know I promised last week
that I wasn't going to
give any more notes.

66
00:03:54,534 --> 00:03:58,402
But, guys, come on,
that last charge, it was...

67
00:03:58,871 --> 00:04:00,031
How do I say this?

68
00:04:00,440 --> 00:04:01,998
It was a
soul-sucking embarrassment

69
00:04:02,075 --> 00:04:03,906
that made me ashamed
to wear the uniform.

70
00:04:03,977 --> 00:04:05,001
(MEN SCOFFING)

71
00:04:05,078 --> 00:04:07,205
Luke Bauer?
Where's Luke?

72
00:04:07,513 --> 00:04:08,912
Colonel Lassiter, sir!

73
00:04:09,616 --> 00:04:13,985
Luke, what did I say
about the bayonet gag, huh?

74
00:04:14,754 --> 00:04:18,212
Too much. There's gonna be
kids watching this, all right?

75
00:04:18,291 --> 00:04:20,851
We don't want the people
in the grandstands to vomit.

76
00:04:21,060 --> 00:04:25,724
Okay, I know we haven't
reenacted this one
for a while.

77
00:04:26,332 --> 00:04:30,098
But the battle at
Piper's Cove, Kentucky, 186<i>4</i>,

78
00:04:30,169 --> 00:04:31,466
is special to me.

79
00:04:31,537 --> 00:04:35,166
It ended
Confederate Quantrill's plot
to assassinate Lincoln.

80
00:04:35,241 --> 00:04:39,007
And it involved my
great-great-grandfather,
Colonel Muscum T. Lassiter...

81
00:04:39,078 --> 00:04:40,067
Muscum?

82
00:04:40,146 --> 00:04:41,579
What the hell is a Muscum?

83
00:04:41,648 --> 00:04:43,479
It was a very common name
of the era.

84
00:04:45,318 --> 00:04:46,307
<i>History Channel.</i>

85
00:04:46,386 --> 00:04:50,322
ESPN, Gus. Channel 206.
I'm begging you.

86
00:04:51,424 --> 00:04:53,051
Hey, Jules!
Wanna join?

87
00:04:53,126 --> 00:04:54,150
Oh, can I?

88
00:04:54,227 --> 00:04:55,455
I don't know.
Do you have
your own hoopskirt?

89
00:04:55,528 --> 00:04:56,893
I rent one.

90
00:04:57,463 --> 00:04:59,328
Sally Reynolds,
front and center.

91
00:05:00,867 --> 00:05:02,767
You missed your cue, Sally.

92
00:05:02,835 --> 00:05:05,065
The cannon fired,
yet no Sally.

93
00:05:05,138 --> 00:05:07,072
I got stuck
in the hospital tent.

94
00:05:07,140 --> 00:05:09,574
Sergeant Menish had
a quick question
about his homeowner's policy.

95
00:05:09,642 --> 00:05:13,203
How touching. However,
today you are not here
to sell insurance, Sally.

96
00:05:13,379 --> 00:05:15,643
Today you are here to
help me win the Civil War.

97
00:05:15,715 --> 00:05:16,841
And according to
our battle plan,

98
00:05:16,916 --> 00:05:19,612
when the fifth cannon fires
you exit the hospital tent

99
00:05:19,686 --> 00:05:21,677
and you shoot
Captain Quantrill
off his horse.

100
00:05:21,754 --> 00:05:23,119
There's no need to get nasty.

101
00:05:23,189 --> 00:05:25,487
I agree.
It was totally out of line.

102
00:05:27,226 --> 00:05:29,194
Sorry, I didn't think
you could hear that!

103
00:05:32,065 --> 00:05:34,397
Sally, sweet Sally.

104
00:05:35,068 --> 00:05:39,664
If you do not
point your gun
at Captain Quantrill

105
00:05:39,739 --> 00:05:42,333
and fire at
the prescribed moment,

106
00:05:42,775 --> 00:05:46,404
the audience will not be
able to make heads nor tails
of what we are doing.

107
00:05:46,479 --> 00:05:50,472
And it will appear
as if the evil
Captain Quantrill,

108
00:05:50,550 --> 00:05:54,953
now being portrayed
by our horrifyingly
method-acting Nelson Poe

109
00:05:55,021 --> 00:05:58,115
who happened to roll
way off his mark, by the way,

110
00:05:58,791 --> 00:06:00,019
fell off his horse

111
00:06:00,093 --> 00:06:03,187
and is lying here
for no apparent reason at all.

112
00:06:04,197 --> 00:06:05,755
Get up, Nelson.

113
00:06:07,100 --> 00:06:10,627
Nelson, I swear to God,
if you're sleeping
through rehearsal again...

114
00:06:10,703 --> 00:06:12,102
I said get up!

115
00:06:22,081 --> 00:06:25,539
Okay, either that guy is
a phenomenal actor

116
00:06:26,919 --> 00:06:28,113
or he's dead.

117
00:06:34,827 --> 00:06:38,456
<i>I know, you know</i>
<i>That I'm not telling the truth</i>

118
00:06:38,531 --> 00:06:41,728
<i>I know, you know</i>
<i>They just don't have any proof</i>

119
00:06:41,801 --> 00:06:44,827
<i>Embrace the deception</i>
<i>Learn how to bend</i>

120
00:06:44,904 --> 00:06:49,341
<i>Your worst inhibitions</i>
<i>tend to psych you out</i>
<i>in the end</i>

121
00:07:00,520 --> 00:07:02,681
Oh, come on,
let me in on this.
No.

122
00:07:02,755 --> 00:07:05,451
I was there.
Inexplicably drawn
to the scene.

123
00:07:05,525 --> 00:07:07,049
I was meant to
solve this case.

124
00:07:07,126 --> 00:07:08,525
It's sort of
like a miracle.

125
00:07:08,594 --> 00:07:10,892
You have been
out there every weekend
we've rehearsed.

126
00:07:10,963 --> 00:07:12,089
And don't think
I didn't see you

127
00:07:12,165 --> 00:07:14,030
trying to throw M&Ms
in the injured
soldiers' mouths.

128
00:07:14,100 --> 00:07:15,863
Okay, first of all,
those were Skittles,

129
00:07:15,935 --> 00:07:17,334
and they have
a rainbow of flavors.

130
00:07:17,403 --> 00:07:19,928
The answer is still no.
Beat it.

131
00:07:29,849 --> 00:07:33,341
Oh! Hold it!
I'm suddenly seeing Nelson.

132
00:07:33,419 --> 00:07:35,353
The bullet,
traveling through the air,

133
00:07:35,421 --> 00:07:37,753
tearing, ripping, pain...

134
00:07:37,824 --> 00:07:40,019
The bullet went
straight through his heart.

135
00:07:41,327 --> 00:07:42,817
This was not
an accident, Detective!

136
00:07:43,029 --> 00:07:45,964
I don't know
how you know that,
and I don't give a rat's ass.

137
00:07:46,032 --> 00:07:48,023
This case is personal.

138
00:07:48,501 --> 00:07:50,765
One of my soldiers was
killed on my watch.

139
00:07:50,837 --> 00:07:53,499
And I, not you,
am going to clean it up.

140
00:07:54,407 --> 00:07:55,499
We clear?

141
00:07:55,575 --> 00:07:58,043
I wouldn't have gone
with something as traditional
as "we clear?"

142
00:07:58,110 --> 00:08:01,807
You could've
gone foreign, right?
<i>Comprende? Capisc?</i>

143
00:08:01,881 --> 00:08:05,874
Could have had
a little fun with it.
You dig my gist, sweetpants?

144
00:08:07,620 --> 00:08:09,087
These are just suggestions.

145
00:08:09,155 --> 00:08:11,783
...and to you,
the Central
Reenactment Committee,

146
00:08:11,858 --> 00:08:14,827
I say as of today,
the event next weekend
is still on,

147
00:08:14,894 --> 00:08:16,418
pending an investigation.

148
00:08:16,496 --> 00:08:18,123
Now, most of you are cops.

149
00:08:18,197 --> 00:08:22,463
Should we find any evidence
that this was not an accident
and do not make an arrest,

150
00:08:22,535 --> 00:08:25,060
we will re-evaluate
at that time.

151
00:08:25,972 --> 00:08:27,701
Now that said,
Detective Lassiter,

152
00:08:27,773 --> 00:08:31,106
I want to know how,
I want to know who,
I want to know why.

153
00:08:31,878 --> 00:08:32,867
(GROANS)

154
00:08:32,945 --> 00:08:33,969
Oh, it...

155
00:08:34,046 --> 00:08:37,243
It's kind of hard to get off.
It takes a long time
to unstick the glue.

156
00:08:40,219 --> 00:08:41,584
All right.

157
00:08:41,921 --> 00:08:42,910
(RIPPING)

158
00:08:42,989 --> 00:08:44,889
Ooh!
MAN: Oh, yeah.

159
00:08:47,894 --> 00:08:48,883
(CLEARS THROAT)

160
00:08:50,830 --> 00:08:52,297
Thank you, Chief.

161
00:08:52,932 --> 00:08:54,058
Pending the coroner's report,

162
00:08:54,133 --> 00:08:56,624
I'd have to say
there are no indications
of foul play.

163
00:08:56,702 --> 00:09:01,469
The general consensus is
that a live round got
mixed in with our blanks.

164
00:09:01,874 --> 00:09:05,241
Mr. Mahoney is the
regiment's munitions expert
and jeweler,

165
00:09:05,311 --> 00:09:08,405
one of
Santa Barbara's finest.
He can expand on this.

166
00:09:08,481 --> 00:09:09,812
Mr. Mahoney.

167
00:09:09,882 --> 00:09:12,874
As you know, Detective,
we had live-round
target practice

168
00:09:12,952 --> 00:09:14,010
this past weekend.

169
00:09:14,086 --> 00:09:16,316
Along with you,
we assumed a musket ball

170
00:09:16,389 --> 00:09:18,220
got stuck
in one of our rifles,

171
00:09:18,291 --> 00:09:19,519
laid there unseen,

172
00:09:19,592 --> 00:09:23,824
and then a blank was inserted
during the last rehearsal...

173
00:09:24,931 --> 00:09:28,298
Poor Nelson.
A terrible, terrible,
tragic accident.

174
00:09:29,902 --> 00:09:32,234
The battles meant
so much to him.

175
00:09:32,305 --> 00:09:35,502
Anyway,
this is an official
police investigation.

176
00:09:35,808 --> 00:09:38,971
So let's focus
on our schematic
and nail down the specifics.

177
00:09:39,045 --> 00:09:40,444
Detective O'Hara,
please.

178
00:09:40,513 --> 00:09:41,502
Hey.

179
00:09:42,548 --> 00:09:44,743
What's the deal,
why do you keep
staring at me?

180
00:09:46,218 --> 00:09:47,981
One. It's our understanding

181
00:09:48,087 --> 00:09:49,884
that the victim was shot
off his horse

182
00:09:49,956 --> 00:09:51,389
at the top of
the creek bank here...

183
00:09:51,457 --> 00:09:52,446
(GUNSHOT)

184
00:09:53,125 --> 00:09:54,149
And then rolled

185
00:09:55,494 --> 00:09:56,961
to the creek bed here.

186
00:09:57,163 --> 00:09:58,926
Two.
We know Nelson was
facing west,

187
00:09:58,998 --> 00:10:00,363
so we're gonna
focus our attentions here

188
00:10:00,433 --> 00:10:02,594
on the opposite bank
where we assume
the shot originated.

189
00:10:04,036 --> 00:10:05,094
Assume.

190
00:10:06,639 --> 00:10:08,266
Detective?
Spencer?

191
00:10:08,341 --> 00:10:12,300
What about three,
the missing bullet?

192
00:10:12,778 --> 00:10:16,339
I saw it ripping
through Nelson's body,

193
00:10:16,415 --> 00:10:18,383
in through the front,
out through the back.

194
00:10:18,451 --> 00:10:20,715
And it still
hasn't been found.

195
00:10:21,687 --> 00:10:23,314
Wait.
How do you know all that?

196
00:10:23,389 --> 00:10:25,482
Lassy,
you wanna take this one?

197
00:10:25,558 --> 00:10:28,049
He had an "episode"
in the hallway.

198
00:10:28,127 --> 00:10:30,595
Look,
I can handle this myself.

199
00:10:31,998 --> 00:10:35,161
Nelson, Nelson, you're going
to have to speak up.
You're teeny!

200
00:10:37,169 --> 00:10:39,000
You were shot
through the heart?

201
00:10:39,472 --> 00:10:41,167
Now, that was
privileged information!

202
00:10:41,240 --> 00:10:42,298
I didn't say anything.

203
00:10:42,375 --> 00:10:44,434
(SHUSHING)
Are you sure about this?

204
00:10:46,012 --> 00:10:47,707
It's bold,
but I'll run with it.

205
00:10:50,282 --> 00:10:54,013
He says people don't get
shot through the heart
by accident.

206
00:10:56,322 --> 00:10:58,290
He says he was murdered.

207
00:10:59,525 --> 00:11:00,583
You're hired.

208
00:11:03,929 --> 00:11:04,918
You told them what?

209
00:11:04,997 --> 00:11:07,329
Gus, she was hot,
and she was dressed
as a nurse.

210
00:11:07,400 --> 00:11:08,697
You know
how I feel about that.

211
00:11:09,268 --> 00:11:11,327
Oh, come on,
what was I supposed to do,
not impress her?

212
00:11:12,304 --> 00:11:14,568
Plus, the tiny figurine made
a very convincing argument.

213
00:11:14,640 --> 00:11:17,006
I don't know how
you're gonna prove murder
with two lousy bullet holes.

214
00:11:17,076 --> 00:11:21,012
Oh, relax. I did some
checking on Nelson Poe,
nobody liked him.

215
00:11:21,213 --> 00:11:24,148
Ever.
And second of all...

216
00:11:24,216 --> 00:11:25,342
What?

217
00:11:27,319 --> 00:11:28,616
Dude, I don't have
a second of all.

218
00:11:28,688 --> 00:11:32,124
And we know Nelson was
on top of the ridge,
facing the Union soldiers

219
00:11:32,191 --> 00:11:34,386
over here when he was shot.
So Schwartz, take Team A,

220
00:11:34,460 --> 00:11:35,484
check out that high grass.

221
00:11:35,561 --> 00:11:38,257
O'Hara, take Team B,
start going over the ridge.

222
00:11:41,967 --> 00:11:42,956
Do it.

223
00:11:43,102 --> 00:11:44,091
MEN: Yes, sir.

224
00:11:45,004 --> 00:11:45,993
(CHUCKLING)

225
00:11:47,640 --> 00:11:49,505
Find something amusing?

226
00:11:49,575 --> 00:11:52,135
Mildly amusing.
More odd.

227
00:11:52,211 --> 00:11:54,702
Delightful,
in a queer sort of way.

228
00:11:55,081 --> 00:11:57,174
For your edification,
the reenactment
of the battles...

229
00:11:57,249 --> 00:11:58,341
Edification?

230
00:11:58,784 --> 00:12:00,046
Yeah, edification.

231
00:12:00,119 --> 00:12:03,714
Is that legal?
Like, in public.
Public edification's legal?

232
00:12:03,789 --> 00:12:05,017
It means
for your information...

233
00:12:05,091 --> 00:12:06,581
Why didn't you
just say that?

234
00:12:06,659 --> 00:12:09,651
For your edification,
the reenactment of battles,

235
00:12:09,729 --> 00:12:12,721
battles fought
by our forefathers
to preserve this Union,

236
00:12:12,798 --> 00:12:14,459
is a sacred trust.

237
00:12:14,900 --> 00:12:16,333
What are you guys
doing here, anyway?

238
00:12:16,402 --> 00:12:17,630
I'm a bit of
a Civil War buff.

239
00:12:17,703 --> 00:12:19,136
I'm reading the dirt.

240
00:12:19,205 --> 00:12:21,036
The trees.
The hot dog stand.

241
00:12:21,107 --> 00:12:23,473
No real information there,
but they do great sauerkraut.

242
00:12:23,542 --> 00:12:25,703
I may even be able to
help you name a suspect.

243
00:12:25,778 --> 00:12:29,009
Look, I told you,
we're 95% sure this was
an accidental shooting.

244
00:12:29,081 --> 00:12:30,548
What about the other 5%?

245
00:12:30,616 --> 00:12:32,811
If I am wrong,
we will hold
a press conference,

246
00:12:32,885 --> 00:12:35,786
you two will be
cordially invited to
say "I told you so."

247
00:12:36,555 --> 00:12:40,924
Seems fair. Hey...
Can I wear your face wig?

248
00:12:47,133 --> 00:12:48,760
What are you doing?

249
00:12:48,834 --> 00:12:51,325
Shockingly,
Lassiter is holding out on us.

250
00:12:51,570 --> 00:12:54,266
I do not think that he thinks
that this was an accident.

251
00:12:54,406 --> 00:12:55,634
What do you mean?

252
00:12:55,708 --> 00:12:58,472
I saw three names checked off
the roster on his clipboard.

253
00:12:58,544 --> 00:12:59,738
What names?

254
00:12:59,812 --> 00:13:02,110
Gus,
I thought you'd never ask.

255
00:13:30,643 --> 00:13:32,508
What is this?
The battlefield.

256
00:13:33,512 --> 00:13:36,003
Based on what?
The briefing room board
at the police station.

257
00:13:36,081 --> 00:13:37,776
You did this from memory?
Yes.

258
00:13:37,883 --> 00:13:39,578
You said you saw it
for two minutes.

259
00:13:39,652 --> 00:13:41,586
Right, two whole minutes.

260
00:13:42,221 --> 00:13:43,210
You got problems.

261
00:13:43,289 --> 00:13:46,781
Factoid!
The musket is accurate
from 30 yards.

262
00:13:51,163 --> 00:13:52,323
Poe.

263
00:13:53,833 --> 00:13:54,822
G.C.

264
00:13:54,900 --> 00:13:55,889
G. C?

265
00:13:59,505 --> 00:14:00,597
George Cheslow.

266
00:14:00,673 --> 00:14:02,868
George Cheslow?
From sixth grade?

267
00:14:02,942 --> 00:14:03,931
Little Georgie!

268
00:14:04,009 --> 00:14:05,636
He's, like, a dentist now.

269
00:14:06,679 --> 00:14:07,976
Really?

270
00:14:09,148 --> 00:14:10,376
See you in six months.

271
00:14:12,418 --> 00:14:13,578
We go in,
we check it out.

272
00:14:13,652 --> 00:14:15,950
See if George Cheslow had
any reason to murder somebody.

273
00:14:16,522 --> 00:14:17,784
Pop out.

274
00:14:17,857 --> 00:14:20,382
Mr. Guster.
The dentist will see you now.

275
00:14:20,459 --> 00:14:21,949
Sweet.
Whoa!

276
00:14:22,027 --> 00:14:25,463
Me? My teeth are gorgeous.
You said the appointment
was for you.

277
00:14:25,531 --> 00:14:27,499
Right.
For me to do
some snooping.

278
00:14:27,566 --> 00:14:29,932
Because I'm
a much better snooper
than you are.

279
00:14:30,002 --> 00:14:31,026
You just keep him occupied.

280
00:14:31,103 --> 00:14:32,365
Occupied how?

281
00:14:33,239 --> 00:14:35,867
(MUMBLING UNINTELLIGIBLY)

282
00:14:36,842 --> 00:14:38,366
Gus, stop it. Be a man.

283
00:14:41,480 --> 00:14:43,744
What's he saying?
He says his teeth
are gorgeous.

284
00:14:45,050 --> 00:14:49,180
I'm sorry, Shawn, but
the reason you have to
be here, too, is?

285
00:14:49,255 --> 00:14:53,385
George, Gus has phobias.
And being alone in
a dentist chair is one.

286
00:14:53,726 --> 00:14:54,852
He could snap at any moment.

287
00:14:54,927 --> 00:14:56,326
This is actually
for your own protection.

288
00:14:56,395 --> 00:14:58,226
Last time
he bit off an index finger.

289
00:14:58,797 --> 00:15:02,255
Thankfully, I was there.
They were able to save
everything but the nail.

290
00:15:06,005 --> 00:15:07,836
Oops. <i>Pardonne-moi.</i>

291
00:15:08,340 --> 00:15:09,773
Honey,
can I talk to you
for a minute?

292
00:15:09,842 --> 00:15:11,969
Oh, sure.
Gentleman, duty calls.

293
00:15:21,053 --> 00:15:24,386
Oh, and the credit card
won't go through.
Do you have any cash?

294
00:15:24,456 --> 00:15:25,923
Oh, sure.

295
00:15:26,191 --> 00:15:28,887
I've got tennis,
then dinner with Karen.

296
00:15:34,733 --> 00:15:36,997
Okay, I'll hit
an ATM, that's...

297
00:15:37,069 --> 00:15:38,195
Don't wait up if I'm late.

298
00:15:38,270 --> 00:15:41,103
Oh, okay. All right.
Bye, sweetie.
Good shopping.

299
00:15:41,373 --> 00:15:42,362
(GROWLS AFFECTIONATELY)

300
00:15:44,376 --> 00:15:45,468
Ah, yes.

301
00:15:46,211 --> 00:15:48,236
George,
I heard you got married,
but, wow, huh?

302
00:15:48,314 --> 00:15:50,339
I know what you're thinking,
"What's wrong
with this picture?"

303
00:15:50,416 --> 00:15:51,713
But, you know,
where is it written

304
00:15:51,784 --> 00:15:54,252
that the ugly guy
never gets the girl?

305
00:15:55,220 --> 00:15:56,278
Everywhere, man.
Yeah.

306
00:15:56,655 --> 00:15:57,644
(THUDDING)

307
00:15:57,723 --> 00:15:58,747
(EXCLAIMS IN PAIN)

308
00:15:58,824 --> 00:16:03,784
No, we're fine.
We're better, you're fine.
Don't worry about it.

309
00:16:04,229 --> 00:16:05,628
Let's see here.

310
00:16:06,799 --> 00:16:10,428
So how is married life
treating you these days,
George?

311
00:16:10,502 --> 00:16:13,699
Everything...
Everything solid?

312
00:16:14,974 --> 00:16:16,498
Why are you
snooping around here, Shawn?

313
00:16:18,077 --> 00:16:19,840
You think I did this

314
00:16:19,912 --> 00:16:22,005
because Erlene was
having an affair with Poe?

315
00:16:22,081 --> 00:16:24,106
Huh?
You didn't know.

316
00:16:27,353 --> 00:16:30,447
Of course I knew, George.
I'm a psychic.

317
00:16:30,656 --> 00:16:32,521
It was over, completely over.

318
00:16:32,591 --> 00:16:35,151
I'm beyond it
and Erlene's beyond it.

319
00:16:35,227 --> 00:16:38,958
At least,
I think she is. I...

320
00:16:39,131 --> 00:16:40,655
I had some gauze...

321
00:16:40,733 --> 00:16:43,497
It's right...
If I could just...

322
00:16:45,471 --> 00:16:47,598
Oh, there you go.
Thank you.

323
00:16:49,808 --> 00:16:53,642
George, do you wear
your glasses out on
the battlefield?

324
00:16:53,812 --> 00:16:55,677
Oh, I want to,
but Lassiter won't let me.

325
00:16:55,748 --> 00:16:57,739
He says they're not
of the period.

326
00:16:59,585 --> 00:17:01,075
Well, if it makes you
feel any better,

327
00:17:01,153 --> 00:17:02,415
Gus here doesn't think
you did it.

328
00:17:02,488 --> 00:17:03,477
Neither does Shawn.

329
00:17:03,555 --> 00:17:07,321
Well, thanks, guys,
I appreciate that. Oops!

330
00:17:07,393 --> 00:17:08,951
Oops?
Small cavity.

331
00:17:09,028 --> 00:17:10,154
I don't have
any cavity in my mouth...

332
00:17:10,229 --> 00:17:11,389
It's right on the surface.
Don't worry about it.

333
00:17:11,463 --> 00:17:12,555
(EXCLAIMING)

334
00:17:12,631 --> 00:17:17,159
There we go.
There's my trooper.

335
00:17:18,203 --> 00:17:20,296
Listen, Georgie,
nobody's drilled my mouth
for anything...

336
00:17:20,372 --> 00:17:22,203
(MUMBLING UNINTELLIGIBLY)

337
00:17:24,309 --> 00:17:25,640
George?

338
00:17:27,146 --> 00:17:28,170
Why am I surprised?

339
00:17:28,247 --> 00:17:30,681
It is a funny coincidence.
Hey, Jules.

340
00:17:31,316 --> 00:17:33,045
George,
I hate to say this,

341
00:17:33,118 --> 00:17:35,518
but you're under arrest
for the murder of Nelson Poe.

342
00:17:35,654 --> 00:17:37,645
What?
On what grounds?

343
00:17:37,723 --> 00:17:38,985
You said
it was an accident.

344
00:17:39,058 --> 00:17:41,185
We discovered
a stack of love letters
at Nelson's house

345
00:17:41,260 --> 00:17:43,751
indicating he was having
an affair with your wife

346
00:17:43,829 --> 00:17:45,456
and that you had
threatened to kill him.

347
00:17:45,931 --> 00:17:47,228
(SCOFFING)
Oh, come on.

348
00:17:47,633 --> 00:17:49,965
I am so disappointed in you.

349
00:17:54,239 --> 00:17:56,173
All right.
Okay, okay, okay.

350
00:17:58,944 --> 00:18:00,309
(MUMBLING)
You got the wrong man.

351
00:18:01,814 --> 00:18:03,008
What did he say?

352
00:18:04,216 --> 00:18:06,081
You've got the wrong man.

353
00:18:09,755 --> 00:18:11,518
First, I told you so.

354
00:18:11,590 --> 00:18:14,957
Secondly, I think
George Cheslow is
an innocent man.

355
00:18:15,027 --> 00:18:17,359
Yeah, you know, he's right.
We do have a paper-thin case.

356
00:18:17,429 --> 00:18:19,954
I mean, all we've got is
motive, means and opportunity.

357
00:18:20,032 --> 00:18:22,626
Look, guys.
I had a dream last night.

358
00:18:23,135 --> 00:18:25,899
I was sipping iced wine
with a baby tree monkey.

359
00:18:25,971 --> 00:18:27,871
And I fell and I landed
in a wooded area.

360
00:18:27,940 --> 00:18:31,273
And that's where
I saw Nelson Poe get shot.

361
00:18:31,343 --> 00:18:35,780
Only, in my dream,
the shooter was much closer
than I originally thought.

362
00:18:36,782 --> 00:18:39,148
This is a minie ball,
am I right?

363
00:18:39,218 --> 00:18:40,617
Where did you get this?
Your desk.

364
00:18:40,686 --> 00:18:45,680
Now, it's common knowledge
that minie balls cause huge
gaping holes in human flesh

365
00:18:45,757 --> 00:18:47,850
which leads to
a quandary in my dream.

366
00:18:47,926 --> 00:18:51,760
Why was Nelson Poe's
exit wound so small?

367
00:18:52,965 --> 00:18:55,695
If George Cheslow had been
in that wooded area,

368
00:18:55,767 --> 00:18:59,225
he was way too far
to make a shot that caused
such a little hole.

369
00:18:59,304 --> 00:19:02,398
Whoever shot Nelson was
much, much closer.

370
00:19:02,474 --> 00:19:05,841
And this "whoever" would be...

371
00:19:05,911 --> 00:19:07,173
Engelbert Humperdinck.

372
00:19:07,246 --> 00:19:08,474
So you've got nothing.

373
00:19:08,547 --> 00:19:10,777
Thank you for the random
speculation. Goodbye.

374
00:19:10,849 --> 00:19:14,341
Mr. Spencer, if you can't
name names, I'm afraid
he's right this time.

375
00:19:14,419 --> 00:19:16,512
Fine, I'll get you a name.

376
00:19:17,956 --> 00:19:20,151
And I'm gonna
get you a woman.

377
00:19:22,361 --> 00:19:25,853
"Afraid he's right"?
"This time"?

378
00:19:28,367 --> 00:19:32,303
It's a gift, actually,
for my son.
A surprise of sorts.

379
00:19:33,272 --> 00:19:37,572
This way he, my son,
will be able to keep track
of time for a change.

380
00:19:37,643 --> 00:19:40,305
Kid was late at birth,
he's been late ever since.

381
00:19:40,379 --> 00:19:44,907
Now, he is going to have
a gold pocket watch
just like mine.

382
00:19:45,918 --> 00:19:47,249
I've had mine for 30 years.

383
00:19:47,319 --> 00:19:51,085
I see. Now, the inscription.
What would you like it to say?

384
00:19:51,523 --> 00:19:52,990
"Shawn,

385
00:19:53,992 --> 00:19:56,756
"don't lose this watch,
Henry Spencer."

386
00:19:56,828 --> 00:19:58,318
Spencer.

387
00:20:00,899 --> 00:20:01,991
What, too much?

388
00:20:02,067 --> 00:20:06,663
No, no. It's just that
your son is no doubt familiar
with your last name.

389
00:20:06,872 --> 00:20:09,397
It might contradict
the sentiment.

390
00:20:09,942 --> 00:20:12,308
All right,
what would you suggest?

391
00:20:13,478 --> 00:20:15,810
"Love, Dad"?

392
00:20:16,181 --> 00:20:20,140
"Love, Dad." Well,
why don't you just put
"Kissy, kissy"?

393
00:20:20,219 --> 00:20:22,449
Right, too mushy.
No problem.

394
00:20:22,521 --> 00:20:24,785
So, before we go any further,
let's see.

395
00:20:24,856 --> 00:20:27,689
Vintage gold pocket watch.
Gold chain.

396
00:20:27,759 --> 00:20:31,718
Taxes and engraving,
comes to a total of...

397
00:20:33,699 --> 00:20:35,064
Wait, wait, wait.

398
00:20:35,133 --> 00:20:38,967
Where's my discount?
I'm ex-cop.
Half the regiment's cop.

399
00:20:39,037 --> 00:20:40,629
I thought we agreed on $<i>4</i>00.

400
00:20:40,706 --> 00:20:43,971
Oh, yes, we did.
But at $<i>4</i> per engraved letter,

401
00:20:44,042 --> 00:20:46,977
that adds a total of $210.

402
00:20:47,045 --> 00:20:52,005
All right, take away "Shawn,"
"this watch", "Spencer."

403
00:20:52,818 --> 00:20:55,116
How much does
that come out to?

404
00:20:55,954 --> 00:20:59,219
$56 for the engraving
plus tax,

405
00:20:59,291 --> 00:21:00,690
$<i>4</i>60 even.

406
00:21:00,759 --> 00:21:03,557
And what does
the revised inscription read?

407
00:21:03,629 --> 00:21:05,824
"Don't lose, Henry."

408
00:21:07,132 --> 00:21:10,329
Clean, to the point.
I like it.

409
00:21:10,469 --> 00:21:11,629
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

410
00:21:11,703 --> 00:21:12,692
Come in.

411
00:21:13,605 --> 00:21:15,869
Mr. Guster, I know
you said you didn't want
to be interrupted,

412
00:21:15,941 --> 00:21:17,738
but there is a Lieutenant
Crunch here to see you.

413
00:21:17,809 --> 00:21:19,003
Crunch?

414
00:21:19,077 --> 00:21:20,840
Actually, I've been promoted.

415
00:21:22,180 --> 00:21:23,169
It's Captain Crunch.

416
00:21:24,249 --> 00:21:25,648
Thank you.

417
00:21:28,420 --> 00:21:29,717
Not in a thousand years.

418
00:21:29,788 --> 00:21:32,052
Dude, we're joining
that regiment.
No, we are not.

419
00:21:32,124 --> 00:21:34,388
They're down to 30 guys.
Please,
I have a meeting in...

420
00:21:34,459 --> 00:21:35,926
And this mystery is
still wide open.

421
00:21:35,994 --> 00:21:39,088
Gus, think about it.
Camping out under the stars.

422
00:21:39,164 --> 00:21:44,659
Living history.
Eating beans and rotten meat
with men who reek of valor.

423
00:21:44,736 --> 00:21:46,169
There's just one thing
you haven't considered

424
00:21:46,238 --> 00:21:48,263
in this perfect scenario
of yours, Shawn.

425
00:21:48,340 --> 00:21:49,671
That's not true.
I've considered everything.

426
00:21:49,741 --> 00:21:53,199
Really?
And what role would I play
in this production of yours?

427
00:21:53,278 --> 00:21:54,506
I don't... What do you...

428
00:21:54,579 --> 00:21:56,069
What role would I play

429
00:21:56,148 --> 00:21:57,740
in the midst of
all those hardcore

430
00:21:57,816 --> 00:22:00,910
down-to-the-last-detail
Civil War re-enactors?

431
00:22:01,353 --> 00:22:02,786
Would I be...
No.

432
00:22:02,888 --> 00:22:05,220
Gus, no.

433
00:22:05,290 --> 00:22:08,316
Okay, then maybe would I be...
Never.

434
00:22:08,593 --> 00:22:10,686
Who are you talking to?
You're talking to me.
This is me.

435
00:22:10,762 --> 00:22:12,662
Then what, Shawn?
What would I be?

436
00:22:12,731 --> 00:22:17,168
Because I tell you, there is
no way, no way, that I would
ever, never ever...

437
00:22:17,703 --> 00:22:20,069
May I please tell you
what I was thinking?

438
00:22:20,138 --> 00:22:21,230
What?

439
00:22:21,740 --> 00:22:23,799
I was thinking <i>Glory.</i>

440
00:22:24,676 --> 00:22:26,940
I was thinking Denzel.

441
00:22:27,846 --> 00:22:31,077
Did you just say Denzel?
As in Denzel Washington?

442
00:22:31,483 --> 00:22:32,780
No, the other Denzel.

443
00:22:32,851 --> 00:22:35,411
Of course.
And we'll put you
on a horse,

444
00:22:35,487 --> 00:22:38,183
and we'll give you
your own sword.

445
00:22:38,256 --> 00:22:39,848
You're gonna have
a chestful of medals.

446
00:22:39,925 --> 00:22:43,190
You can be
anything you want.
You can be a pilot.

447
00:22:43,261 --> 00:22:45,491
The Air Force wasn't
formed until World War I.

448
00:22:45,564 --> 00:22:47,725
That's fair.
So you can't be a pilot.

449
00:22:47,799 --> 00:22:51,132
Look, I called Mr. Mahoney,
he's Mr. Uniform,

450
00:22:51,203 --> 00:22:54,502
and I told him to make you
something spectacular.

451
00:22:55,574 --> 00:22:57,235
Denzel Washington.

452
00:23:03,115 --> 00:23:06,949
Captain Mahoney, you said
we needed recruits? <i>Voilà.</i>

453
00:23:07,719 --> 00:23:11,519
Welcome aboard, son.
I didn't expect you
back so soon.

454
00:23:11,590 --> 00:23:14,058
Don't know if
the uniforms are ready yet.

455
00:23:14,126 --> 00:23:15,957
But it is spectacular?

456
00:23:16,027 --> 00:23:18,757
You saw <i>Glory?</i>
This is the best we had.

457
00:23:18,830 --> 00:23:20,161
Well, come along.

458
00:23:20,232 --> 00:23:21,722
I told you.

459
00:23:22,667 --> 00:23:25,898
GUS: Wow, Captain,
it's quite an establishment
you've got here.

460
00:23:25,971 --> 00:23:27,768
My sanctum sanctorum.

461
00:23:33,678 --> 00:23:37,114
Fine jewelry, yes.
Even my vintage
pocket watch collection.

462
00:23:37,182 --> 00:23:41,141
But above all, the finest
Civil War memorabilia

463
00:23:41,219 --> 00:23:43,653
and props
west of the Mississippi.

464
00:23:44,356 --> 00:23:47,883
I can attest to that.
I've repaired
nearly half of them.

465
00:23:47,993 --> 00:23:51,986
Sally. I am so happy
to see you,

466
00:23:52,063 --> 00:23:54,964
though I'm a little
disappointed you're not
wearing your nurse's uniform.

467
00:23:55,033 --> 00:23:58,002
Griffin called me, frantic,
saying we needed
one more outfit.

468
00:23:58,069 --> 00:23:59,127
You okay with that?

469
00:23:59,204 --> 00:24:01,832
I sure am. It's just a shame
you didn't dress me.

470
00:24:01,907 --> 00:24:03,704
Still time for that.

471
00:24:05,911 --> 00:24:07,344
Aside from reenacting,

472
00:24:07,412 --> 00:24:08,936
Sally insures
half the regiment.

473
00:24:09,014 --> 00:24:11,778
Auto policies, homeowners.
Even theft.

474
00:24:11,850 --> 00:24:14,876
Speaking of which,
Griff, I'm thinking
of insuring my legs.

475
00:24:14,953 --> 00:24:16,580
Sort of like Mary Hart.

476
00:24:16,655 --> 00:24:19,681
What do you think,
three, five million a haunch?

477
00:24:19,758 --> 00:24:22,283
Keep in mind my calves are
like carved marble.

478
00:24:22,360 --> 00:24:24,920
That's not the kind
of policy she writes.

479
00:24:24,996 --> 00:24:26,327
So she wrote yours?

480
00:24:26,398 --> 00:24:30,528
Of course. And it's worth
more than both your legs
put together.

481
00:24:30,802 --> 00:24:33,965
Does that policy include
plastic explosives?

482
